steps.message:
17 TFLOPS — much worse. Loading weights from kernel memory inside the hot loop adds significant global memory traffic. The weight_reg preload is better.

Let me go back to the 80-VGPR version (which did 24.0 TFLOPS, close to 24.5) and find a way to bridge the gap.

The 80-VGPR version:
```cpp
float weight_reg[KD][KH][KW]; // preloaded
...
uint32_t v0 = ds_read_b32(...);
uint32_t v2 = ds_read_b32(...);
uint32_t v4 = ds_read_b32(...);
// 6 float conversions
// 10 fmacs
```

The original at 155 VGPRs:
```cpp
float weight_reg[KD][KH][KW];
IO_DTYPE input_reg[KD][KH][KWR][KW_PACK]; // 45 entries
// 45 ds_read_b32
wait
// 150 fmacs
```

The original batches all ds_reads with one wait, then does all fmacs. My version interleaves reads+compute. The overhead of more wait cycles is the difference.

Let me try a version that keeps all 45 ds_reads but then processes per (d,h) in the compute phase. This way: one wait for all 45 reads, then compute phase with no further waits, and the compiler can reuse register slots for input data if we process (d,h) sequentially:

